Q1: What are the Catholic holy days of obligation and other holy days?
Q2: Which days are considered holy in the Catholic Church?
Q3: What are the Catholic holy days of obligation?
Q4: What are the Catholic holy days that are not days of obligation?
Q1Ans:
["The Catholic holy days of obligation vary by country, but generally include:
- Solemnity of Mary, Mother of God (January 1)
- Epiphany (January 6, or the nearest Sunday)
- Ascension (40 days after Easter, observed in some countries)
- Assumption of Mary (August 15)
- All Saints' Day (November 1)
- Immaculate Conception (December 8)
- Christmas (December 25)

Other significant holy days include:
- Good Friday (date varies, during Holy Week)
- Pentecost (50 days after Easter)
- Corpus Christi (date varies, usually in June)
- Feast of the Holy Family (Sunday within Christmas Octave)
- Feast of the Sacred Heart (Friday after Corpus Christi)
- Feast of the Annunciation (March 25)
- Feast of St. Joseph (March 19)
- Feast of the Assumption (August 15)
- Feast of the Nativity of John the Baptist (June 24)
- Feast of the Transfiguration (August 6)
- Feast of the Assumption of Mary (August 15)
- Feast of All Souls (November 2)

Please note that some of these days are obligatory only in certain countries or regions, and the specific dates can vary slightly depending on local calendars."]
Q4Ans: ['Solemnity of Jesus Christ, King of the Universe', 'Solemnity of Mary, Mother of God', 'Ascension of Jesus Christ', "All Saints' Day", 'Immaculate Conception of the Blessed Virgin Mary', 'Christmas Day']
Q3Ans: ['The Solemnity of Jesus Christ, King of the Universe, which is celebrated on the last Sunday of the liturgical year, usually in late November or early December in many countries.', 'The Feast of the Immaculate Conception of the Blessed Virgin Mary, observed on December 8th, celebrating the belief that Mary was conceived without original sin.', 'The Nativity of Our Lord Jesus Christ, or Christmas, celebrated on December 25th, commemorating the birth of Jesus Christ.', 'The Feast of Saint Joseph, Spouse of the Blessed Virgin Mary, observed on March 19th in many countries, honoring Saint Joseph, the foster father of Jesus.', "The Feast of the Annunciation of the Lord, celebrated on March 25th, marking the angel Gabriel's announcement to Mary that she would conceive Jesus.", "The Feast of the Ascension of Jesus Christ, observed forty days after Easter, usually on a Thursday, commemorating Jesus' ascension into heaven.", 'The Feast of Pentecost, celebrated fifty days after Easter, marking the descent of the Holy Spirit upon the apostles.', "The Feast of the Assumption of the Blessed Virgin Mary, observed on August 15th, celebrating Mary's assumption into heaven.", 'The Feast of All Saints, celebrated on November 1st, honoring all saints, known and unknown.', 'The Feast of All Souls, observed on November 2nd, praying for the souls of the deceased.']
